# LLM Repository Instructions for FreeSWITCH

## Overview
This is a FreeSWITCH codebase - a Software Defined Telecom Stack for VoIP/telecommunications applications. This fork is maintained by Telnyx with bugfixes and stability enhancements. FreeSWITCH is primarily written in C with some C++ components.

## Code Style and Conventions

### General C/C++ Style
- Follow existing indentation and formatting patterns (tabs appear to be used)
- Use consistent variable naming conventions (snake_case for variables, UPPER_CASE for constants/macros)
- Maintain existing function signature patterns and return value conventions
- Preserve existing comment style and documentation format
- Use FreeSWITCH-specific prefixes (SWITCH_*, switch_*) for APIs and types

### FreeSWITCH-Specific Conventions
- All FreeSWITCH APIs use the `switch_` prefix (e.g., `switch_log_printf`, `switch_channel_*`)
- Module functions follow `mod_<modulename>_<function>` naming pattern
- Use FreeSWITCH macros like `SWITCH_MODULE_DEFINITION`, `SWITCH_MODULE_LOAD_FUNCTION`
- Follow the modular architecture - modules are in `src/mod/` subdirectories
- Configuration uses FreeSWITCH XML config patterns

### Memory Management
- Always check for NULL pointers before dereferencing
- Use FreeSWITCH memory pool system (`switch_core_alloc`, `switch_core_session_alloc`)
- Avoid direct malloc/free - use FreeSWITCH memory management APIs
- Use `const` qualifiers appropriately for read-only data
- Be especially careful with session and channel memory management

### Error Handling
- Use FreeSWITCH status codes (`switch_status_t`, `SWITCH_STATUS_SUCCESS`, etc.)
- Check return values of all function calls that can fail
- Use consistent error code conventions throughout the codebase
- Provide meaningful error messages using `switch_log_printf`
- Handle edge cases and boundary conditions properly

## Build System

### Primary Build System
- This project uses autotools (configure.ac, Makefile.am files)
- Run `./configure` followed by `make` to build
- Module-specific Makefiles are in each mod directory
- Respect existing compiler flags and optimization settings
- The build supports cross-compilation scenarios

### Module System
- Modules are dynamically loadable (.so/.dll files)
- Each module has its own Makefile.am in its subdirectory
- Modules must be enabled in `modules.conf` to be built
- Follow existing module template patterns (see mod_skel)

### Dependencies
- Core dependencies include: APR, Sofia-SIP, SpanDSP, various codec libraries
- Check configure.ac for required vs optional dependencies
- Telnyx-specific additions include Boost, Poco, ZMQ, Berkeley DB

## Telecommunications/Audio Specific

### Real-Time Processing
- Be mindful of sample rate dependencies and buffer sizes
- Maintain precision in audio/signal processing calculations
- Consider numerical stability in codec and DSP algorithms
- Avoid blocking operations in media processing threads
- Preserve existing bit-exactness where required for codec compliance

### Session Management
- Understand FreeSWITCH session lifecycle and state management
- Use proper channel variables and APIs
- Handle call setup, media handling, and teardown correctly
- Be aware of SIP protocol requirements and FreeSWITCH abstractions

### Threading and Concurrency
- FreeSWITCH is heavily multi-threaded
- Use FreeSWITCH thread primitives and synchronization
- Be aware of session locks and avoid deadlocks
- Understand the core thread architecture

## Performance Considerations
- Avoid unnecessary memory allocations in real-time media paths
- Consider cache-friendly memory access patterns
- Maintain existing optimization strategies
- Profile critical paths when making changes
- Be mindful of CPU usage in high-call-volume scenarios

## Testing and Validation

### Module Testing
- Test modules with various call scenarios
- Validate codec encode/decode paths
- Check for memory leaks using FreeSWITCH's built-in tools
- Test with different SIP scenarios and edge cases
- Ensure compliance with relevant telecommunications standards

### Integration Testing
- Test with real SIP phones and soft clients  
- Validate interoperability with different SIP stacks
- Test under load conditions
- Verify configuration file parsing and validation

## Security Considerations
- Follow secure coding practices for network-facing code
- Validate all external inputs (SIP messages, RTP packets, etc.)
- Be aware of buffer overflow and injection vulnerabilities
- Use FreeSWITCH's built-in security features appropriately
- Never log sensitive information like credentials

## Before Making Changes
- Understand the FreeSWITCH architecture and call flow
- Check for similar patterns elsewhere in the codebase  
- Consider impact on both call setup and media processing
- Verify changes don't break existing module compatibility
- Test with multiple codecs and transport protocols
- Ensure changes work with FreeSWITCH's event system

## Configuration and XML
- FreeSWITCH uses XML for configuration
- Follow existing XML schema patterns
- Use FreeSWITCH's configuration API for runtime config changes
- Validate configuration parameters appropriately
- Provide meaningful error messages for configuration issues

## Logging and Debugging
- Use FreeSWITCH's logging system (`switch_log_printf`)
- Follow existing log level conventions (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR)
- Include channel UUID in session-related logs
- Avoid excessive logging in high-frequency code paths
- Use appropriate log channels for different subsystems

## Codec and Media Handling
- Understand FreeSWITCH's codec negotiation system
- Handle media frame timing correctly
- Support various audio/video formats as appropriate
- Follow existing patterns for codec implementation
- Handle format changes and re-INVITE scenarios properly

## Documentation
- Document public APIs using existing comment patterns
- Update relevant configuration examples
- Maintain inline documentation for complex algorithms
- Follow FreeSWITCH documentation conventions